Analyzing What's Important in CS:GO
¶

By: Daniel Chen and Teddy Popescu
¶

Full squad of 5 Counter-Terrorists
¶

Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CS:GO) is a multiplayer first person shooter game developed by Valve. CS:GO was one of the most popular first person shooter games at the time of its release in 2012, and remains popular today, routinely achieving daily peak player totals above 1 million. In CS:GO there are two teams of 5 players each, the attacking “terrorists” and the defending “counter-terrorists”.

The goal in reach round for the Terrorists is either to kill all 5 Counter-Terrorists, or plant a bomb at one of two bombsites before the round time is over, and defend it from being defused for 40 seconds. For counter-terrorists the win condition is either to kill all 5 Terrorists, prevent the bomb from being planted for the duration of the round time, or to defuse the bomb at any point after it is planted. There are 7 maps to play on, over 20 unique weapons to choose from, and multiple options for grenades and equipment.

In our tutorial, we used game data scraped from games played on ESEA’ servers. ESEA is a platform that hosts games as a third-party to Valve’s matchmaking service that promotes a more secure anti-cheating program. We aim to use this data to examine which weapons are most successful in winning rounds and killing opponents, analyze how much the overall team’s economy has an effect in them winning a round, and compare how the map that is played has an overall impact on the match. Through these analyses we want to gain insights on the strategies that are used to win gunfights and win rounds, and try to make a model that can accurately predict which side will win a given round. We hope that through this tutorial we are able to provide interesting insights on the important factors to winning in CS:GO, and motivate people to try and pick up the game.

Graphing Weapon Kill Output
¶

At the core of each match of CS:GO is the weapons that are used by the players. There are over 20 weapons in CS:GO split up into 4 categories: Pistol, SMG, Rifle, and Heavy (Shotguns). Each of these categories, and each unique weapon inside them operate in different ways. SMG’s prioritize faster rates of fire, with their damage output being lower, pistols are less expensive to buy but deal less damage and are not automatic, rifles fire generally slower but have high damage output, and shotguns fire slowly but fire multiple pellets for each shot. We will graph the percentage of kills registered across this data based on the weapon that delivered the kill to see if there are any weapons that are either sparingly used, or used at a higher rate.

With the different properties of each weapon class, it is important to see how often each one is used during a match to see if any weapon class has an advantage or disadvantage.

plt.ylabel('Kill Count Percentage')
plt.show()

This graph shows the percentage of all kills logged in our dataframe that were attributed to each weapon type. For general understanding, the Equipment and Unknown bars in this graph can be ignored, as the “weapons” in these categories only produce kills in extremely rare circumstances, and the purpose of these “weapons” is not to get a kill. Through this graph, we can see that over 50 percent of kills were registered with some kind of rifle. This is over double the amount of the next closest weapon type, that being the pistol. On the other end, the heavy (shotgun) weapon type is used an extremely small amount of the time. Although this graph is good at demonstrating the general trend of which type of weapons are mostly used by players, it does not take into account the different scenarios surrounding each round in the game.

In a game of Counter-Strike, there are 30 rounds, with the first team to reach 16 winning the game. Throughout the game, each player builds up a certain amount of cash, through events such as winning a round, losing a round, planting the bomb, killing an enemy, etc. The money that a player has accrued is used for them to purchase weapons, with some weapons being easily purchased, and others being more expensive. When a team does not have enough money to buy their primary weapons of choice, a popular strategy is for that team to “save” their money, purchase very little, in an attempt to be able to purchase those weapons next round.

Therefore a round in CS:GO can be characterized in many ways: a “normal” round, where a team has enough money to buy their desired weapons, “eco” round, where a team buys next to nothing, “semi-eco” where a team purchases some weapons, but very little, and a “force-buy” round where a team does not have the necessary money to buy what they want, but spends all of their available money anyway. On top of this, there is the beginning “pistol” round where both teams begin the game with little money, and only have money to purchase pistols. Therefore, we want to observe the most commonly used weapons for each round type in CS:GO.

In each weapon category, the difference in price for each individual weapon is very small and does not greatly impact weapon choice inside of a given category, so we will first see which weapons are most commonly used inside each weapon class, and see how the usage of those most popular weapons changes depending on round.

weapons = []
count = []
x = 0

for weapon in kills["wp_type"].unique():
    wep_type = []
    count = []
    for specific in kills[kills["wp_type"] == weapon]["wp"].unique():
        wep_type.append(specific)
        count.append(kills['wp'].value_counts()[specific] / kills['wp_type'].value_counts()[weapon])
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,5))
    plt.bar(wep_type, count, color=colors[x])
    plt.title('Percentage of Kills for each ' + weapon)
    plt.xlabel('Weapon Name')
    plt.ylabel('Kill Count Percentage')
    plt.show()
    x += 1

These graphs show each weapons’ percentage of kills in their weapon category, and through these graphs we can see the weapons that are most popularly used in each category. Despite being in the same class, some weapons are clearly used at higher rates than others, this is due to each weapon having slightly different characteristics to the others in its class, that players may find useful, such as some rifles having a scope to allow a player to zoom in. We discount the Equipment and Unknown weapon types due to the prior reasoning. Grenades are a weapon type that is very cheap in game, and is purchasable in every round type. As a result, we also discounted Grenades from our by-round analysis. To determine the popularity of the weapon, we selected any weapon that accounted for above 15 percent of its weapon type’s kills to be included.

Predicting Round Win/Loss based on Round Characteristics
¶

Kills play a massive part in determining who wins the round/match in CS:GO. One of the win conditions for both sides is eliminating the whole enemy side, and kills enable each side to more easily complete their round objective to win. Despite this, kills are not the only factor when it comes to determining who wins a round. Other factors, such as how long the round took, how much money each team had to begin the round, which side the team is on, and whether the bomb was planted during the round play a crucial role as well. We aim to use these many factors to help create a model that can accurately predict round win/loss.

Round Time
¶

There is a timer for each round in Counter-Strike, and each round takes a certain amount of seconds from the round start to the round end. There are several phases to a counter-strike round, starting with a 15 second “freeze time” period where teams can purchase their weapons and equipment. The “main round” has a 1 minute and 55 second timer, where if the terrorist side cannot eliminate the counter-terrorist side or plant the bomb, then they lose the round and the round ends. If the bomb is planted at any point, the round shifts to a “post-plant” phase, where there are 40 seconds for the counter-terrorists to try and defuse the bomb. Regardless of if the round enters the post-plant phase or not, there is a 3-5 second ending phase after the round result has been decided before the next round starts. As a result of the round timer that the terrorist team must work in, there are many different strategies for the terrorist side to try and win the round, from taking their time in planting the bomb, to trying to immediately start fighting. We want to try and see the optimal round time taken to win a round as the terrorist side.

Even though the differences in win percentage are slight, given the large size of our dataset, even these seemingly slight differences are important. From this graph, we can see that terrorists won less than 50 percent of rounds in which the round took a small amount of time, and perform the best when they either took a medium, or very long amount of time in the round. We believe that the reason for the terrorist side’s struggles during shorter rounds is due to the common occurrence of playing a much faster style of round when having little money. This is because when not having proper weapons at your disposal, the common thought is that it is tough to play a more normal pace of round, and therefore many teams elect to “rush” a bombsite to try and either catch the counter-terrorist team off guard, or to end the round quickly and move on to the next where they will have better weaponry.

Additionally, we believe that the dip in terrorist round win-percentage for rounds taking 120-150 seconds, is as a result of terrorists not being able to plant the bomb in the normal round timer, and electing to run out the clock and save their weapons for the next round. This is similar to our reasoning that terrorists are able to win the rounds that are extremely long, as these rounds would not reach these lengths of time without the bomb being planted, which we believe is a very important aspect for terrorists winning a round in CS:GO.

Round Win Vs. Team Economy
¶

Another factor that we believe is important is the overall money that a team has going into a round. Having stronger equipment and weaponry should in theory give a massive advantage to a team in being able to win a round.

First, we want to test our previous hypothesis that a possible reason for the lower win percentage in faster rounds for terrorists was due to more of these faster paced rounds not being “normal” buy rounds.

From these bar graphs, we can see that in all rounds in our data, normal rounds were the most common, accounting for slightly more than 40 percent of all rounds. Following this was eco rounds at around 35 percent. However, these values are very different when taking into account rounds that were over quickly, ranging from 29-60 seconds, which was a time range that terrorists preformed relatively poorly in. In these rounds, over 50 percent were eco rounds, with only around 20 percent of these rounds being normal buy rounds. Eco rounds accounted for 20 percent more of all rounds from 29-60 seconds, while normal rounds accounted for 20 percent less of these rounds. The much higher proportion of lower buy rounds in rounds that took 29-60 seconds reaffirms our thought that the terrorist win percentage in these round lengths is partially due to the terrorist side having less money in rounds that end up taking a shorter amount of time.

Now, we want to see just how much of an impact the total team economy has on the team’s winning percentage. We will split this analysis up into the Terrorist and Counter Terrorist sides to see if there are any discrepancies in total team economy and round-win percentage across the two sides.

A second notable feature is the sudden dip in win percentage that both teams experience from 2,001-5,000 dollars to 5,001-10,000 dollars. This could be due to the fact that when a team has around 3,000 dollars, this is usually early in the game, when the other side probably also has around the same low money, whereas when a team has around 8,000 dollars, the other side probably has significantly more money at their disposal.

One hot encoding is a method of transforming categorical data into numerical data by creating a new column for each possible categorical value, and having a 1 if that row contains tha value, and a 0 if not.

The way we analyzed our models is with an error statistic called RMSE.
¶

Essentially RMSE takes the difference between the model’s predicted result, and the actual result, sums the squares of those values for all inputs, and then divides by the total number of input and takes the square root of the value. The result is a final value that represents the overall accuracy for a model.

If you want to learn more about the specifics behind RMSE:

https://www.statisticshowto.com/probability-and-statistics/regression-analysis/rmse-root-mean-square-error/

For our two models for both terrorist and counter terrorist win percentage, the RMSE value was around .5, which is a relatively low value. This indicates that our models were decently successful in correctly predicting if the terrorist or counter terrorist team won a round based on that team’s total equipment value. Our linear regression model might have performed even better if not for the dip in win percentage around 5,000 dollars, as a line does not represent that region accurately, and our model would have predicted more terrorist rounds won in that area than there should have been.

Analyzing the Balance of Maps:
¶

In CS:GO, each match is played on one map, of which there are 8 to pick from in this dataset. These maps have a huge variety in their setting, size, and characteristics. Some maps have very open spaces and are very large, such as Overpass, while others are much more cramped and consist of tighter walkways, like Inferno. A map like Mirage, for instance, is known for being very small and having many different connections to different parts, and is almost half the size of a large map like Overpass. Nuke, meanwhile is a vertical map, with the two bomb sites being placed on top of each other on different floors in the facility.

Each map is unique in its own way, and has key differences that cause strategies to be different and for games to play out differently depending on the map. Some maps are much easier for a player to snipe in due to having tight corridors, while other maps are much easier to hide behind cover due to being in an open setting. Due to these differences, it is believed by many players that certain maps are easier to play on certain sides, and that due to the map design, a map is either “terrorist-sided”, “counter-terrorist-sided” or “balanced”. We want to see all the maps’ Terrorist vs. Counter-Terrorist win percentage and see if there are any maps that stand out as having disproportionate balance in it’s win percentage for each side.

First we will graph the terrorist/counter-terrorist win percentage in total, and for each of the 8 maps individually to see if there are any notable differences from the overall. We will do this using the meta_demos dataset from our master database, as it has the map information for each round played.

In [178]:
x = len(maps[maps["winner_side"] == "Terrorist"]["winner_side"])

From just counting Terrorist vs. Counter Terrorist round wins, we can see Terrorists win around 51 percent of rounds to Counter Terrrorist’s 49 percent. This gives us a baseline to test each individual map to see if any map has a split that is significantly different from the general win percentage.

These are pie charts that display the round win percentage for each of the 8 specific maps. Most of these maps seem decently balanced and close to the overall round win percentage pie chart, with Mirage being impressively balanced at almost an exact 50/50 split. However, we can see two maps in particular that do seem to deviate from this balance, with Dust2 boasting the highest Terrorist round win percentage at 54.3 percent, and Nuke boasting the highest Counter Terrorist round win percentage at 57.9 percent.

Dust 2 and Nuke have reputations for being a more terrorist and counter-terrorist sided map respectively. Dust 2’s layout allows the Terrorist side to immediately have a sight-line into the Counter-Terrorist territory, which is generally seen as giving the Terrorists an advantage, while Nuke is known for being cramped, and easier to navigate from the Counter-Terrorist side of the map, which has given it it’s reputation as the most Counter-Terrorist sided map. Even if these pie charts seem to indicate that those reputations are earned, we want to see if these are actually due to the map not being a balanced map, or if these results can be explained through sample variation in our data.

The way that we will test if these results could reasonably be attained if the map was truly 50/50 balanced is through statistical hypothesis testing. Hypothesis testing is a technique that allows you to make a hypothesis, and then test the feasibility of that hypothesis being true or not given the data that you have. In our case, the null hypothesis, or our hypothesis that we will either prove or disprove, is that both Dust 2 and Nuke are 50/50 balanced maps, and that the results we get are explained through sample variation, rather than the maps themselves being unbalanced in nature.

To see the probability of obtaining our results despite the map having a 50/50 round win percentage split, we will use a binomial CDF analysis. This is an analysis that returns the percentage of getting results as or more extreme than the results that were attained in the data. The Binomial CDF function calculates this score based on

1. The Number of Successes (rounds won by the team with less overall win percentage)
2. The Number of Trials (total rounds played)
3. The Probability of a Success (.5, if we assume a balanced 50/50 split)

For more information about the applications of using Binomial CDF:

https://www.mathworks.com/help/stats/binocdf.html

The percentage scored returned is said to be the “p-value” of the hypothesis test, and generally if this value is .05 or greater, than it is reasonable to assume that the null hypothesis is true, and if the p-value is less than .05, then the null hypothesis is rejected. In our case, this equates to either concluding that the map is balanced and that the results are due to sample variation, or that the map is unbalanced.

In [187]:
temp = maps[maps["map"] == "de_nuke"]
x = len(temp[temp["winner_side"] == "Terrorist"]["winner_side"])
n = len(temp) 
p = 0.5
q = 0.5
print("Probability of de_nuke getting round win percentage results this or more extreme than this is: " + str(round(binom.cdf(x,n,p), 1)))

temp = maps[maps["map"] == "de_dust2"]
x = len(temp[temp["winner_side"] == "CounterTerrorist"]["winner_side"])
n = len(temp) 
p = 0.5
q = 0.5
print("Probability of de_dust2 getting round win percentage results this or more extreme than this is: " + str(round(binom.cdf(x,n,p), 1)))
print()

Probability of de_nuke getting round win percentage results this or more extreme than this is: 0.0
Probability of de_dust2 getting round win percentage results this or more extreme than this is: 0.0

We rounded our percentage results to the nearest decimal place to neatly display our p-value. Through performing a binomial cdf for both the results of our Nuke and Dust 2 sample data, we can see that the probabilities of obtaining results that are this extreme or more extreme are essentially zero. In order to accept the null hypothesis, the standard accepted p-value is .05, as this is seen as a reasonable percentage to assume that the results can be due to sample variation. However, our p-values are nearly 0 for obtaining these results, which means that we reject the null hypothesis, and therefore we conclude that Dust 2 is in fact terrorist-sided and not balanced, and that Nuke is counter-terrorist sided.

Bombsite B on de_inferno
¶

Given that the p-values for the two most extreme maps in terms of round-win percentage were incredibly low, being nearly 0, this gives us reason to believe that the overall win percentage split that we previously thought indicated that the game as a whole was balanced between the two sides, might actually not be due to sample variance, and might be proof that CS:GO as a whole is not a perfectly balanced game between the terrorist and counter-terrorist sides.

In [188]:
x = len(round_data[round_data["winner_side"] == "CounterTerrorist"]["winner_side"])
n = len(round_data) 
p = 0.5
q = 0.5

print()

Probability of CS:GO getting round win percentage results this or more extreme than this is: 0.0

Our probability calculation for CS:GO as a whole shows that the probability of getting a 51/49 round-win percentage split is almost 0 percent. Therefore, we can conclude that in nature, CS:GO is slightly Terrorist-sided. Even though a 51 percent terrorist win percentage seems very small, given our large sample of data, even this slight difference cannot be explained simply by sample variation. CS:GO is a complicated game, with so many different factors that can impact the overall balancing. From the exact prices of certain weapons, to how much damage they deal, to each of the individual maps and how they are designed, these moving parts combine to make it almost impossible to perfectly balance the game between the Terorrist and Counter-Terrorist sides. Although the round win percentage split in our data shows that there is not a perfect balance in the game, given the difficulty of trying to make the game as balanced as possible a 51-49 percent split is an impressive accomplishment for the developers of CS:GO.
